{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643668"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:56:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:56:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18004"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18004"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.09,0.74,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10718"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64194"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27043"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe axis is the name given to the C2 cervical vertebra (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a feature of the axis vertebra?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior and posterior arches","Anterior and posterior tubercles","Dens","Groove for vertebral artery","Lateral masses"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edens\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the odontoid process, is a prominent feature of the axis (C2 vertebra). It projects superiorly and provides a pivot around which the atlas (C1 vertebra) and the head rotate. This is crucial for the rotational movement of the head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral masses\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior and posterior arches\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Egroove for the vertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E are features of the atlas (C1 vertebra), not the axis. The atlas supports the skull and allows for nodding movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior and posterior tubercles\u003C/strong\u003E are also features of the atlas, not the axis. These structures are part of the atlas\u0027s arches and serve as attachment points for ligaments and muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The axis (C2 vertebra) is characterised by the presence of the dens, which is a pivotal structure for rotation of the head.","The axis does not have lateral masses, anterior and posterior arches, or grooves for the vertebral artery, which are features of the atlas (C1 vertebra)."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64194"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18004"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21462"}]},"explanatio